values:
it's 3:30 and I'm trying to stay up cause I'm meeting my freshman seminar group at Baker Rink at 5:30 to leave for Bermuda and I'm afraid that if I let myself fall asleep I won't wake up even if Jack does call at 5. I just finished a night of movies: Fight Club in Witherspoon with Nithiya, Emily, Luis, and this girl whose name I don't know and just now Amelie with Jane and Sarah. Missed an outing to the Met with Sarah and Jane this afternoon / evening because of class and Jane being worried about me going through sketchy parts of the city alone. Jane and Sarah almost got arrested at the Met for "trepassing" into a roped-off exhibit. 

This week has been full of late-night midterm studying and paper writing. late Sunday for chem on monday which I miraculously managed to make no stupid math mistakes on. Monday night for bio paper which managed to be a great pain to print, Wednesday till 2:30 at Frist with Emily. Thursday I signed this big six-foot book outside Frist supporting the cause against Global Warming. Our seminar when to the pool to practice snorkeling and Dr. Z gave  us PEI caps which according to Emily makes me look like a backcountry hick. One of these nights, a sleep-deprived and school stressed Waters appeared at my door and I went in search of bagels with her. I've seen way too little of her recently which I'll make an effort to change after break and I never got to say goodbye to her. Last night was "halloween at princeton" - our puppet show fell through for a number of reasons though now we're planning a christmas scrouge show instead. John rather vaguely said he'd take me to the Street a few nights before so I at the last minute decided to be a doll. I got no response from him until almost 12 because he was at some frat party with Adam. For a while there we thought he'd actually stood me up and Jane and Emily were prepared to get revenge. I feel so lucky to have made friends here who really do care and get worried and actually would have given John hell. I finally meet John down by the corner of Blair where he was on P-watch with Adam. We sat down there for like an hour or so talking and then went down to the U-store where we got ridiculously over-priced dumpling that we warmed up back in the kitchen in his dorm which I finally got to see. We found some of the "octagon" just beginning to watch "Independence Day" and pretty much stayed there the entire night watching the rest of the movie and meeting more people as they filtered in and out. I came back at a little past three and was in the bathroom when Jane came back just a little later and freaked when she saw me not in bed and woke emily up who proceded in wake Waters up when I came back from the bathroom. 

It feels really weird to be leaving here in only a few hours if only for a week. Though this may not be the "perfect match school" I can't imagine being anywhere else now and I know I'm really going to miss it even for this week, though I am still so excited for Bermuda. One week seems like such a long time when you live with people 24 hours a day, though these first six weeks have flown past and there's many things I wish I hadn't done, and many more I wish I had.

Despite the fact that's it almost 3 in the morning I feel the need to journal this day / yesterday as it has been one of the most eventful and best days here yet. 
Starting with yesterday night / morning, when I decided to stay in instead of going to the Street w/ Waters. It started as an attempt to spend the night studying but soon Emily and I attacked the very messy common room, soon to be joined by a very delirous and sleep-derived Jane: we put down a rug, set up a lamp, added numerous wall hanging: degas poster, poster that says "a woman without a man is like a fish without a bicycle", food for thought pictures, pictures from a frog poster and a sign above the door that says "which of these frogs is not like the other?" just to screw with people, and a poster sleepy Jane decided to make when she detested this one ugly poster and realized she had pastels - it's a very colorful abstract picture, though quite well done. I must say she's quite hilarious when she's tired - upon finding the pastels she blasted her music despite it being 2 in the morning and the guys below us sleeping and said she'd draw the song ; duck-taping the bookshelves together that technically aren't stackable. 

Finally went to bed around 3 and slept in till 10. Meandered around in the morning - got brunch w/ emily, stephen, and mike - made napkins with love-notes to Keith that we were planning on putting on our trays so they'd go back to the kitchen where we thought he was cleaning dishes only to find that he was swipping cards (which he'd been doing the wrong way for some time). Went back to the room, wandering around again doing chem problem set. Decided to go to lawn parties with Jane at the last moment - wandered around the eating clubs for awhile looking for people - finally went to Quad to catch the end of the Folds and most of Everclear w/ Huan, Waters / Peter, Jane, and numerous other people. Leaving slightly early to miss the crowd. Getting dinner w/ emily and john and most of his z-group; ice cream and walk back with John. Bio reading in the common room, which is now so enticing that we can't help but actually read it. Two consecutive fire alarms - Matt trying to be happy about them. More bio. Study break to find cereal for emily in dining hall (Jane to murray dodge for cookies - I'm glad Jane is warming on us and that we're getting to know her better). We run into Waters who was carrying a huge pan of lazzana which they were apparently going to throw out so we helped her eat part it - discussions of boys and random stuff - tired Waters = loud / funny - we managed to scare Ada away by being too loud. Back to the room for more bio before going off to the computer cluster in Holder to print stuff. Running into Newton and his friends / roommates - climbing through their window to find a bunch of random people in their room - singing happy birthday to a rather disgruntled Sian and writing on their white boards. After printing back to the common room for communal bio reading for emily and I and french for Jane. Grace stopping by at somepoint asking for microwave and laughing at Jane; running into Aba (our RCA) at 2:30. Not quite finishing bio, but emily forcing me to stop and go to sleep, which clearly I'll do soon. But as emily said before she went to sleep, I'm content, it's been a good day.

Some random events that need to be recounted over the past few weeks: 
-the first was that really warm Wednesday before the last snow fall - I stopped at a little Korean (I think) produce place in East Goshen to get coffee before dance. As I walked in I noticed a rather plump and slightly unkempt man walking out. I look away from him, but he just stopped and said "smile little girl" and when I did, he said "now, that's better" and smiled himself. But perhaps what made me smile more, aside from the weather, was the little girl who watched me from the top of the stairs as I poured my coffee and said hello and goodbye in an adorable accent with ten seconds of the other. 

-That Friday was the snow / ice storm - out of school early although the roads weren't too bad then - just wet slush, although I did see an older person skid a little just before turning into Hershey's Mill. Although this is the first winter that I really haven't liked the snow, it is also the first time that I loved spring so much. 

Saturday night my mom and I ventured into the city to see PA ballet do Serenade and Carmina Burana - BBC/BBT went the friday before, but I couldn't go because of the school dance show. Serenade was good, but typical - I mean it was performed for the most part really well. But Carmina's use of the stage lights / set / music / choirs not to mention unique costumes and choereography made it a much more impressive piece.

important / interesting events from the past week:

-last saturday night: coming back from barnes and noble w/ helen, nupur, and bridget - got to king street in malvern when I saw flashing lights of a police car behind me. Strangely I had seen the police car turning around in a parking lot just a ways back - I guess turning around to follow me? Anyway, so I pull over, wait at least five minutes while I completely freak out and scare Nupur / Bridget because it's past curfew. Then the cop, whose a woman, comes up and asks me to pull over into the next street, which scares me more because I think it means that it's something more serious, etc. So she takes an extra five minutes once we pulled off king street and then comes up and quite nicely says that the only reason she's pulled me over is because she thinks one of my headlights is out - I think she may have even used the word "hun". So she has me turn on my lights, all the way on, only to realize that they were perfectly fine and after she shines a flashlight in our faces wishes us a good and safe night and drives off. Spanish music. What's ironic is that on wednesday morning when I drove to the cardealership in exton to give my dad a ride because his car was going in for servicing he told me one of my lights was out and that he'd get it fixed because the police can use it as an excuse to pull you over. I hadn't told him about the saturday night experience so I was just like oh really, I had NO idea...

rest of the weekend consisted of rehearsal and stuff - Christina's birthday is the 13th and I still have to go get her a card or something. Unfortunately she didn't come to class on monday because she didn't have a ride, because her mom's away. Monday I missed stretch because of Mr. Great Valley, although I realized that I probably could have gone to at least part of it, which annoys me, because it's a good class and I really need it especially for my right side which a lot tighter than my left - in part because I think I pulled a huge muscle in my thigh. Only three girls showed up for the ballet part of the dance club dance and someone decided to change the schedule on us making us go before formal wear without telling us - so we were in the bathroom changing when we heard our music and only steph and I made it out it in time - well for the second time of our music - because they had to stop and start it again when they realized no one was on stage ready. So the first part was pretty messed up and it resulted in a picture on the website of me in a bad retire back in my pirouette - Nancy always tells us that it should look perfect from every angle and I guess this is one clear proof that I need to work on that - but my turns are improving - and today I managed somewhat poor triples as donna wished. 

tuesday nancy had us partner which was rather intimidating. We started with double pirouettes on pointe supported by the guy - the guy holds your waist and helps push you around. It's easier than alone in a way, which is good because I can't do clean doubles on pointe. But the thing is that all the guys are amazing and I feel so bad when I realize that I am making them look bad / making it more difficult for them because I'm not clean or I'm not holding my weight well - it's one thing to mess up yourself, but it's something totally different to mess up when someone else is depending on. And christy actually talked to me as we stood behind dan freaking ourselves out - it's funny how she's only started being friendly to me now that she knows I'm her age.
 
friday was the dance club show. It was actually turned out a lot better than I thought it would. And although I'm relieved it's all over now, it's sad that this is my last year and all and really as much as we complained we all did have a lot of fun with it. Steph and I were talking after the show and I was asking her what was going to happen next year with dance club. And she asked me what I'd do if there wouldn't be one next year, and I had to reminder that I'm graduating. And then Julie James said that she was forcing me to go to West Chester and take class with her at Brandywine so she'd have "someone to bitch about" by which she meant to. It made me realize just how many people I'm really going to miss, and even the people I don't see or like nearly as much as Steph or Julie, both of whom I've gotten closer to this year w/ dance and love.

Things I'd like to do on a more daily basis:
-read / hear the news
-write / read 
-listen to music with knowing who / what is it 
   I recently found some old cds that I've been listening to. Namely, Something Corporate. Awhile ago my computer freaked and I had to delete all my music files, and I switched to internet radios..but now I going back to cds...brings back memories, but whatever, there's not much that doesn't anymore
-work on stamina / stretching / conditioning stuff - I really need to get in shape for this summer. I mean I have some muscle but it is really sad just how little stamina I have, and the other dancers for that matter
But in any case I'm pretty excited for the summer - I think it's the first summer that I actually have a lot already planned for: senior week, CPYB from the end of June through July, PLP probably in august again, probably a family trip to my great aunt's ranch in Texas, and of course college preparing, etc. 

But anyway, I think I'm finally realizing just how fast this year is going by - on a day to day basis it seems rather slow, but really I barely know what happened to winter and really I can't fully believe even that we are seniors and we'll be graduating in only three months. 
And I'd never really thought about it before, but there seems to be a big difference between 17 and 18. The younger girls at dance were talking about my age (it never ceases to amaze this one girl that I'm 17 and I can DRIVE) and one girl mistakenly said I was 18 and another girl who knows I'm 17 looked so unbelievably shocked and really I don't blame her: while 17 is still a teenager there's something marking about 18 - like a definite passing from child to adult. I feel the same way about 19 to 20 - Chris just turned 20 and it seemed so weird to me to think of him as 20 because to me we're still both just kids. It's quite scary, really. 

So, I had my Princeton Interview today. I felt it was sortof weird that I was contacting him through his secretary but he kept saying that my mom (who had answered the first call) had talked to him which she never did. But eh I liked him and I think it's funny that he found in college the same thing that I really want - people. Oh and he works for Charlie Anderson's dad and seems fairly well aquainted with the Anderson family. But I think it went fairly well, even though I managed to slightly crinkle my resume during the car ride over - typical I know - ha, I think it's really quite funny how people just assume I am so neat and organized when really it is so not true. I mean there are times when I get slightly complusive and become momentarially neat, but for the vast majority of the time - no. 


ah - livejournal - I don't know if it's a good thing or not that I'm back and honestly I can't say how consistent the posting will be and sorry but many may be private - I think it's something that I can at least be honest with myself - I never knew it'd hurt so much, but really I think it's better this way and I more than deserve so whatever

hmm..I think what I like about poetry is it allows me to say such things that I would probably never be comfortable saying to someone's face..its as though its some hidden language in which I can express everything Im thinking, and its nice just to be able to write it down, even if no one will really understand (granted they are rather vague).

this is just well..i don't know a random jumble :

<lj-cut>A sureil world of love..of couples kissing, friends hugging
   places to see...people to be..
But what lies in the truth of it all..the painful lonely truth 
of wishes and hopes and failues..of words unspoken of words regretted..don't you know...it was you all along..I was too afraid to say it to your face..to open the door to talk..to tell you truth..but you wouldn't know..you wouldn't care, you would forget as the door closes washing me out of your life as you wash the dirt wedged under your fingernails..put on the coat, the make-up, wipe you eyes swish your hair stride out the door and into the world..compose yourself for a hard day..the beggars line up beside you..and you walk on don't stop, don't look..head down head straight one foot in front of the other..but its harder now it takes effort to get out of bed to walk out the door..to face the world you roll down the hill hair covered in snow covered in white frost..lying there as misty breath escapes your lips and you shiver and roll and shiver and breath..to think you're alive..just as alive as anyone else-but life is escaping from you today-maybe it will return tomorrow, I do not know weak and unsure you set out to avoid temptation and follow a path..to hack through an untreated forest to seek a flower on the other side..a kingdom of honesty and love a kingdom of sucess a kingdom where they are innocent of jealousy of hate of misunderstanding..where everyone can lived and be loved..Christians call it Heaven..but that I find myself unable to believe in that..and so I left with a corrupted forest we call Earth and myself nothing more than a bacteria to dirty the clean skin of those I touch..innocent they say..little will they..I try I know..but Im already corrupted and it seems no matter what my intentions are not intrepreted..ahhh people will assume things they will regret..why say what you don't know..those who are patient may hear the truth one day, may come to know me one day..not the truth is anything good or special, just ordinary..and well sometimes rather unordinary thoughts about an unordinary world, complaints and fears and pains..nothing you haven't heard before, nothing special..just me. </lj-cut>

ha..ok so the last entry was not written by me, but rather by Nupur who took over my lj..which I permitted her to do only if she made it clear that it was her and not me..which she obviously didn't do, so I am just telling you that what was written and may be written in the near future is possibly not by me and thus what is said is Nupur's interpretation of my life and not my own, which Im sure will become confusing.

i won't be feeling like myself for the next week or so. i don't know it's thanksgiving break and i want to do something different. so here's a list of things you may or may not know about me, because i don't think people understand me, who i am, what i like, etc. and just assume that i feel a certain way about things. Did you know that... 1. I like vanilla. 2. I am completely against illegal music. 3. I thought that some bits of the dance sequences for A Midsummer's Night Dream weren't well rehearsed. But I liked the play. 4. I had a dream about weird escalators and being a student at Penn. 5. My parents do this weird thing where...like...my dad buys a gift for my mom, and then I give it to her and my mom buys a gift for my dad, but then i'm the one who gives it to him. so they buy each other presents, really, but don't give them to each other directly. 6. I am getting my father a cake bowl for christmas. 7. My mom wouldnt let me do governers school because she wants me to "have fun" this summer and not do something academic, like dance, and even though I would love to dance, i think I should have been able to do governor's school. 8. If I got to the finals for FBLA, i wouldn't have been able to go to governor's school anyway. what's inconveinent is that now i have to go to guidance and tell them to disregard my teacher recommendations and stuff. 9. (Nupur's making me type this) I told Nupur that "Me and my husband are going to run away to Alaska. And it'll be so cold there that you won't be able to function." 10. I think Paddington is handsome for a cat.

hmm..so today was interesting. raining all day..sitting around in chris's dorm with my mom either asking him really stupid questions or just complaining (nothing will change will it)..chris thinking this throw thing my grandmother made for him was actually a rug..eating pistachio nuts...doing ap us work at penn's library and at paul's desk because he left for the day (ha..and having random people thinking I was a Penn student)...hmm...the pod restaurant-it really reminds me of the "Quantam Cafe" the absurd wealth of Wharton because all their alumni go become CEOs of some big company and then go and give penn a whole ton of money..seeing penn's athletic center and wharton building go by through the window of a parking garage window..utter confusion at the ticket station in paoli because a bunch of old ladies didn't see the sign that the ticket counter is closed on weekends and keep going on about how the worker was on break and would be coming right back..

anyway...the 20 list thing that I am finally doing
1. I have a love/hate relationship with urban life
2. I love ballet-it is the one thing thats saves me from the stress and chaos my normal life
3. I have some probably impossible and unrealistic dream of going to Cornell and double majoring in biochemistry or something and dance..
4. I prefer white chocolate
5. I wish I was brave enough to really institute change in my life
6. I always find myself jealous...and I hate it so much
7. I love singing, but like writing poetry, its just sortof something I do when I'm depressed and something that justs sortof mine that I would never do any thing else with because Im really not any good
8. I'm a perfectionist
9. I regret almost everything I do/say 
10. Sometimes, just life in general, and just random people amaze me 
11. I wish I could live myself hundreds of times over and each time just have my life go a different way--there are sooo many things I'd like to do with my life and I know I never have the time /courage to do all of them 
12. A lot of my life is governed by irrational fear
13. I can't wait to go to college
14. language in general greatly interests me
15. I think/know/care a lot more than I'll ever say 
16. In some ways I really am quite a careless person
17. My mood changes really quite frequently, but once again its apparently not that apparent
18. Sometimes I get just so tired of the life that I'm living
19. I really wish I had a distinct language/culture
20. I no longer really know who I am

hmm..meh..the dance: for me at least it was not a good night, and it order to explain sortof what it was like I explain another night that reminds me of this. I had gone to the movies to see Napoleon Dynamite, and this is probably why had I such a negetative opinon of the movie. Not because the movie itself was bad or anything, but because of the events of that night there was no way in which I could have appreciated the sillyness of that movie. I can just remember how it just dragged on and on and how the laughter of the rest of the audience seem to hurt even more. and I can remember the car ride home; it was one of those rides when you're the only car on the road and it was quite dark and you're sitting in the back corner of the car and everyone else is talking, but you just sortof block that out while looking out the window..and for me those rides are always the most depressing and I can remember trying in vain to hold back tears, but ironically noone noticed. Now granted tonight was depressing for a completely different reason and im not going to say exactly why because I'd probably get yelled at for it, but all I'll say is that reason sortof initiated a lot of other things, basically a lot of bad, old memories

I've become to realize that noone really does know me. I mean when the person who I'd say knows me the most thinks that I'm not an emotional person at all, I begin to wonder. But I guess that's sortof what life has done to me; made me keep things to myself, make me hesitant to tell others. As much as I'd like someone to understand me, I think that maybe noone ever will, and yet I have a feeling that there is someone who can just understand me, understand my perspective on life without knowing me that well. 

meh. so auditions were friday. I did alright but I don't think I got in. I mean mrs. leingener doesn't think I'm a good dancer because she's knows that I just started in ninth grade basically,and so she thinks I really don't know what Im doing..which is for the most part true. But even though it would mean a lot to me to get in, I think the fact that I'm taking classes sortof makes it alright. I mean the classes will give me a chance to dance at an advanced level (or at least try for that matter).

this only really applies to Tishna..
um..i don't know if you want any of this, but I thought I'd put it here just in case. This is just some information about dance schools that I found when I was looking for schools this past summer

hmm..first of all the rock west:
   -website: www.therockschool.org and then under each heading it is broken into the rock west or the rock centre. The website makes it seem like you take a placement class where they just see where you are with experience and where they think they should put you, which means they might end up putting you in a class with younger kids, but because you're probably more serious and dedicated than them you;ll probably move up fairly quickly to classes with people closer to your age (also you could probably ask them from the beginning to put you in a class with students your age, even though you're not at the same level). also, even though tuition here may be expensive, I think they do offer scholarships

and here are just some other schools in case you want to look around or whatever:
-Wayne Ballet: I've heard this was a good school, but I never really looked into it, because it is far away
-The Dance Center (Brandywine School for Performing Arts):                        www.thedancecenter.org-partners directly with the Brandywine Ballet Company; pre-professional school like the rock
-Diane Matthews (www.dianematthewsdance.com); more of a community school, its more laid back and not as serious, although the instruction is still good. also, tuition here is going to be quite a bit less than at the rock or the dance center     

also if you got to AOL yellows pages (if you have aol) and type in your adress and then dance instruction it will give you the distances and average times to all the dance studios within a certain radius. Also you can probably sit in or participate in a class at the Rock to get a feel for the teaching, and the instructors, etc.

hmm..ok so apparently someone found my lj and read parts of it that were possibly offensive to someone they knew and then they continued to send those parts to the someone who in turn got hurt by it...so basically through some unnamed (and unknown) middle person several of my lj entries hurt someone else..and its not as though I even meant to hurt anyone, I was just writing my opinons on the matter and it wasn't even as though I was trying to make fun of or put down this someone behind their back..so maybe I will stop writing in here and make my entries private or something..but I don't know that I really want to make them private either..I mean I don't want to hide anything from the world and I certaintly don't want to make it seem as though by hiding my entries from everyone except my "friends" I'll be able to still do things that could potentally be hurtful to people, only they wouldn't be to read them..

meh..i don't know it seems that the past week has changed me, or at least just so oo many things have happened and there are so many things for me to think about, etc.

soo..on saturday i got my permit..my dad took me to the place and we sat for like an hour, but then i finally got called up. ha and i was right before anna (matsiras) so we were taking our tests right next to one another.
and afterwards my dad took me to the empty..well fairly empty parking lot at immaculta to drive around..and everything went well until he had me park between an actual car and the curb..i was fairly fine getting into the parking space, but when i tried to get back out i forgot to switch from reverse to drive and then well yea..it freaked my dad out especailly because there were actually parked cars behind me and he quickly grabbed for the gear shift..
   and then yesterday he also took me driving and we went to a bunch of different places-the highschool parking lot, a really big corporate center in exton, and some neighborhood..just to let me drive and all.

hmm..our one bathroom that was getting redone is finally done and my mom have moved in..my brother and I really aren't allowed to use it though, until our bathroom (the old one) is getting redone and therefore we'll be forced to use the new one..well actually our bathroom has started to get done-my dad took about half the ceiling out yesterday to reveil the original beams and undersides of the boards of the room above (how it would have been originally)..so now there is only have a ceiling and a lot of dust everywhere despite my and chris's efforts to clean it up.
 and several strange things happened...umm saturday i think..first our water heater broke which means taking really really cold showers..and then my mom couldn't get the grill to start (im not too surprised, because she is rather clueless with stuff like that..but then she went to turn on the toaster and it burst into flames..and yyet she still insists that it is fine and useable..

So as for California we left last thursday fairly early in the morning. The flight was pretty normal and all, only you had to pay for both lunch and earphones if you wanted. So we got in to the airport at San Francisco on time an dtook the tram to the rental car place..ha and passed the stop for BART-Bay Area Train. And then we waited and waited for a rental car, until we finally got on and left for Napa valley, where the wedding was held. It took us about three hours to drive up, but it was a really nice drive and once we got into Napa Valley the entire countryside was covered with expensive looking houses and wineries and lots of beautiful vineyards..hundreds upon hundreds of straight rows of grapevines.
     So we got to our hotel in Rutherford (in napa valley) and well it was reaallly nice, like the room had a really big bed and fireplace and stainglass window. It was really cool because all of it was done in the style of southwestern architecture..let's just say that we wouldn't have stayed there if we had actually had to pay for it.
     With the time change and all we went to bed early so didn't really do anything until the next day, when we actually went out and did a bit of touristy stuff. We went to Sterling vineyards and took a gondala up the mountain to the winery (the vineyards were at the base of the mountain with the winery at the top) and then we went to the "Old Faithful" of California which was a rather pitiful gyser located in the more hickish outskirts of Napa Valley. And somehow it took us almost the whole day to do those two things and drive around and come back in time for the bridal dinner where I got to meet my uh..cousins and second cousins by marriage. 
     The next day I went shopping in Napa with the Liz's (the bride) three daughters, their friend (who had come with them to the wedding) and my cousin. And it became rather apparent just how rich they are..(Liz has barely worked and simply inherited a lot of money. (at least my uncle murray-the groom - who is also quite rich has worked his entire life as an investment banker to become rich)..we went into this one store with lots of really pretty skirts and dresses, but they were all at least eighty dollars, but all her daughters seemed to think that that price wasn't too bad if the skirt was nice, whereas my cousin and I were just like no way with that price.
     As for the actual wedding is was reallly nice. It was held at a private home and vineyard-and the house was practicaly a mansion with a lot of antiques and surrounded on one side by a vineyard and the other by gardens. The cermony itself only lasted for about ten minutes. ha and the "minister" was a jewish friend of my uncle and his wife who probably just took some online course to become a "minister"..but then again it was california so it really didn't matter. After the ceremony all the adults sat down for an elaborate six-course dinner, while us kids sat at a different table and ate more uh normal food..it slightly annoyed me that they seperated us, but seing the maturity of some of my cousins it was very understandable.
       The next day was then the brunch to send the couple off. and then we ourselves left for San Francisco. It took us seven hours to get from napa to the city, because we decided to go west to teh coast and take route 1 south which is very very beautiful but also rather dangerous as it curves up and down the side of mountains. So we finally got into the city and strangely that day was quite like our first one in California.
       As was our second day in the city like the seocnin Napa. In th morning we went down to Fisherman's warf to the aquarium and then to a ferry boat which took us on an hour tour around the bay going under teh golden gate bridge and then around Alcatraz..we decided to not take the boat that would have given us time actually on Alcatrz, because of my mom's bad knees. Then we took a cable car up to uncle and uh..aunt's appartment..which given their financial state was very large and nice and had a really nice view of the financial district and of the bay. hmm..so i saw this movie last night, it was called Whale Rider. It was meant to be a sortof informative film, but it was more of a movie in the sense that it had a complete plot and all..basically it was about a patriarchal religion/society of sorts in New Zealand that was lead by a male cheif. and this tribe (or whatever) believed that their ancestors were the whales that inhabit the waters of the shores on which they live. so basically there the current cheif has come from a long line of cheifs and his son has a child, and of course the grandfather wants the child to be a son, because then they could be the new chief, but of course the child was a girl..and it was there belief that because the line was messed up (with the birth of a girl) their family line went back to that of the ancestors. considering that the girl "couldn't" be a chief, the grandfather started a school for all the boys to chose one to be a chief, but they all fail and so he feels as though he has failed and he calls to the ancestors for help..but they don't listen to him..so his granddaughter hearing him call, decides to try calling herself..and they listen to her, and come..literally..meaning that after a few days the beaches are lined with beached whales who all came to the girl's calling ..so the tribe finds the "leader" whale and trys to pull it back into the sea, hoping that the others will follow..but they can't and as they walk away, the girl goes and gets on the whale's back urging the whale to live and go back to see and it listens to her and goes back..restoring herself as the cheif of the tribe, even if she's "only" a girl..

the interesting thing about the actor who played the girl, was that the producer simply went to area schools and went into all the classes looking (without the children knowing) for the right girl for the part..meaning that the girl she chose had little, if any, actual acting experience and yet did an amazing job..the only thing that kindof annoyed me about this actor is that she mentioned (this was in a "behind the scences" thing) that during one emotional scene she had to "cry" as she was saying a speach to her neighbors..and apparently they had to switch tapes in the middle of this scene, and because switching them takes so long, she had to basically stand there and "cry" in all for about forty mintues..and she said that when she was finally done she had everyone else crying (because she had done such a great job with it ) but that she didn't know why they were and that she was just happy to not have to "cry" anymore..which means basically that she never got into that role..that she never actually became that girl..and yes she was only a child herself (although she looked to be about 15) and this was her first role ever, but still..
